article.description: The Golden State Warriors were a bunch of teenagers the last time their team was this good.
article.headline: Warriors reach .500 for first time since 1994
article.linkText: Golden touch: Warriors win sixth straight
article.story:
OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- The Golden State Warriors were a bunch of teenagers the last time their team was this good.
 
Arenas
Gilbert Arenas was only 12, and didn't even begin playing basketball for another year. Arenas had 22 points and nine assists as the Warriors defeated the Indiana Pacers 107-100 Tuesday night for their sixth straight win -- the team's longest winning streak in nearly nine years. The Warriors improved to 30-30, the franchise's first time at .500 since April 24, 1994. That's the same year the organization last reached the playoffs. "We all thought we were going to be here. We didn't know when," Arenas said. "Anything's doable in this league right now. We're playing with a lot of confidence. We're playing like we're going for a championship and nothing can stop us." Ron Artest had 32 points, seven rebounds and five assists, and Jermaine O'Neal added 21 points and six boards for Indiana, which has lost six straight road games. The Central Division-leading Pacers had won the past three meetings with the Warriors. Golden State's winning streak is the team's longest since winning eight straight in April 1994, when the Warriors finished 50-32. Tuesday's victory gives them their highest win total since going 30-52 in 1996-97. Arenas can't tell you much about that 1994 team, except that Chris Mullin was playing on it. "I was into getting in trouble, being a bully," Arenas said with a smile. Jason Richardson and Erick Dampier each had 20 points for the surging Warriors, who have won nine of 12. They are 16-6 against the Eastern Conference, including 12-2 at home. Dampier also had four blocked shots. "It's a great story what's gone on thus far," first-year coach Eric Musselman said. O'Neal scored back-to-back baskets, then Reggie Miller scored off a turnover to pull the Pacers within 86-83 with 8:16 left. But the Warriors, looking much like a playoff team, answered with a 10-0 run, six points by sparkplug Earl Boykins and two straight dunks by Antawn Jamison. The Warriors beat the Pacers to loose balls and controlled the boards down the stretch. Boykins had all 10 of his points in the final period. Dampier was fired up from the beginning against his former team. Three of his dunks were in the first quarter, when he scored 10 points and the Warriors shot 55.6 percent. Last month, the 6-foot-11 Dampier called Musselman ``Musselhead'' out of frustration for his playing time, but they seem to have patched things up. Musselman joked about it before the game. "I got called Musselhead. It's natural to think you'd like to bench that guy and not give him any touches," Musselman said. "I think we have a good relationship." The Warriors held the Pacers without a field goal for more than four minutes late in the third quarter. "A lot of teams can say it's a tough shooting night when you don't win," O'Neal said. "Those guys came out and played hard. They have a good young team that's going to have a lot of say in the next couple of years. We didn't match their energy." It has been a rare sight to see fans on their feet in the first half, if at all, in recent years here. The crowd of 16,409 was raucous not just because of all the dazzling dunks, but also in an effort to help their team get defensive stops, often hollering "DEE-FENSE!" Golden State is tied with Houston for ninth in the Western Conference, two games behind Phoenix for the final playoff spot. In their previous four wins, the Warriors held opponents under 40 percent from the field, their longest such streak since November 1967, when the club held seven straight opponents under 40. Indiana shot 40 percent. In a sign of how things would go for the Warriors this game, Dampier tipped a ball higher than the backboard and it banked in on the way down with 3:16 left in the first quarter for a 26-23 lead. That play came after he blocked a shot by Artest on the other end, then he dunked the following trip down. Game notes
Warriors F Danny Fortson did not dress for the game because of a death in his family. He missed practice Monday and also Tuesday's shootaround. ... O'Neal returned to the Pacers after missing practice Sunday and Monday to be in Indianapolis with his family in the wake of the self-inflicted gunshot wound suffered by his stepfather, Abraham Kennedy, on Saturday. ... Manute Bol attended the game on Chris Mullin bobblehead night. ... The Pacers haven't won on the road since beating New Orleans on Feb. 12. ... Boykins scored 10 or more in the fourth quarter for the eighth time.
